Both ‘Asina ’ and ‘Asellus ’ were well-known ‘cognomina’; the former in the family of the Scipiones (see the story in Macrob. Sat. 1. 6. 28), the latter in ibe annia and the Claudia gens. The jest on the name was a time-honoured one, for Cicero (de Or. a. 64. 258) quotes it as having been made by Scipio Africanus liin. against Ti. Claudius Asellus. There is nothing else to connect the cognomen either of Asina or Asellus with the gens Vinia, of which the first member who became famous is the T. Vinius of Tac. Hist. 1 passim.
